ce:section.ce:para:
To enhance morphological characterization, three-dimensional structures of both pristine and functionalized membranes were reconstructed using tomographic techniques, providing a more precise study of the porous materials (Fig. 3
                           ). The overall characteristics of the materials indicate an enhancement in material density and development of tightly packed domains. Regions of high density are identifiable by the rise in X-ray attenuation, marked by the gradual emergence of domains. XTM images indicate that the packed purple domains were most prominent in T-CNF-M, followed by T-CD-CNF-M, with P-CNF-M exhibiting the least intensity. The data indicated that the CNF density was highest in T-CNF-M and lowest in P-CNF-M. The advanced computational reconstruction of the acquired 2D projections yielded intricate 3D representations. This sophisticated model encompasses both visual and quantitative data, utilized to assess the membrane's porosity. Table 3
                            displays the results of the membrane porosity measurements. All the membranes displayed nearly uniform pore distribution, as indicated by the distinct homogeneous appearance of purple-hued regions due to enhanced X-ray attenuation. The overall porosity measured in a 0.015 mm3 sample was 43.63 %, 32.58 %, and 37.69 % for P-CNF-M, T-CNF-M, and T-CD-CNF-M, respectively. The open and closed porosity of these membranes varied in relation to the density of the CNF within the membranes. There is no evidence of cracking or significant nanofiber aggregates suggesting no inherent defects were produced during manufacturing. Comparable observations were documented by Martoia et al. [54] with TEMPO-oxidized cellulose nanofiber foam.
